{"key":"post-12410775","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>12410775</id>\n<content>If you're getting culture slants, don't use them for direct inoculation of grains.&amp;nbsp; Use them for long-term storage, and only remove a tiny piece of mycelium twice a year or so to inoculate agar in petri dish(s).&amp;nbsp; Use wedges from the petri dishes to inoculate the rye jars.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;If you do agar wedges, you open the lid and drop it in.&amp;nbsp; If you work quickly, it has a high chance of success.&amp;nbsp; All you need for your glovebox is a little bleach mixed with water in a sprayer.&amp;nbsp; In fact, you could probably just go with plain water, which will attract and trap any contaminants that contact the sides or bottom of the box.&amp;nbsp; This keeps your box explosion proof, and you keep the flame for your tools outside the box.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;I prefer regular mouth quart jars.&amp;nbsp; The smaller opening allows for fewer contaminants to enter when you lift the lid.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>12413527</next>\n<prev>12410358</prev>\n<first>12344497</first>\n<last>12730895</last>\n<when>1271553575</when>\n<utime>04/18/10 04:19 AM</utime>\n</post>"}